  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Training staff on detecting potential money laundering\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Legal regulations\n- Compliance with Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering standards\n\n5. Due diligence\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Investigating high-risk transactions\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant legal penalties, including fines and potential criminal charges, for failing to meet these obligations.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of anti-money laundering requirements?",
